  "prompt": "What is the diffusion of water through a membrane?",
  "response": "The diffusion of water through a membrane is known as **osmosis**. Osmosis is a specific type of diffusion that refers to the movement of water molecules across a selectively permeable membrane. This membrane allows the passage of water but restricts other solutes or larger molecules. \n\nIn the context of osmosis, water moves from an area of lower solute concentration (higher water potential) to an area of higher solute concentration (lower water potential). This movement continues until there is an equal concentration of solute on both sides of the membrane or until the system reaches equilibrium. \n\nOsmosis is critical for maintaining cellular function and homeostasis in living organisms, as it helps regulate the balance of fluids and solutes in cells and tissues.",
